data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — the most common `Thread.Abort` migration scenario. Here's the full breakdown:

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggered — the exception type still exists but is never thrown |

Your code will **compile with warnings** but **crash at runtime** when the timeout path is hit.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout.
            task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Unwrap AggregateException from Task.Run to match original behavior
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw new AggregateException(task.Exception!.InnerExceptions);

        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Preferred overload — lets the work cooperate with cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Fire-and-forget work** | The first overload (no token) returns immediately on timeout, but the `Task.Run` delegate **keeps running** in the background. `Thread.Abort` used to forcibly kill it — cooperative cancellation cannot. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores cancellation** | If `work` does `Thread.Sleep` or blocking socket reads, it won't respond to the token. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` or async I/O. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here). Let it propagate everywhere else. |

## Caller Migration

```csharp
// OLD — works but work keeps running after timeout
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeResult(), 
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// NEW — work actually stops on timeout (preferred)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return BuildResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**The fundamental shift**: .NET Framework could yank the rug out from under a thread. Modern .NET requires the work to **voluntarily check** the token. Always prefer the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload so work actually stops.
